2. High-Level Architecture
Overview

HBnB follows a layered architecture that separates system responsibilities into different layers. This approach improves system organization and allows developers to maintain and expand the application more easily.

The system architecture consists of three main layers:

Presentation Layer
Business Logic Layer
Persistence Layer

Presentation Layer

The Presentation Layer handles communication between the client and the application. It exposes API endpoints and processes incoming requests from users.

Responsibilities include:

Receiving client requests

Validating request data

Sending responses back to the client

Business Logic Layer

The Business Logic Layer contains the core models and services responsible for implementing the application’s rules and behaviors.

Responsibilities include:

Managing domain entities

Processing application logic

Coordinating interactions between entities

Persistence Layer

The Persistence Layer manages database operations and ensures that data is stored and retrieved correctly.

Responsibilities include:

Saving data to the database

Retrieving stored data

Managing database access through repositories

