4. API Interaction Flow

The system processes user operations through a series of interactions between the client, API, business logic components, repositories, and the database. These interactions are illustrated through sequence diagrams.

User Registration Flow

The User Registration Sequence Diagram illustrates how a new user account is created.

Flow description:

The client sends a POST request to the API to create a new user.

The API controller receives the request and validates the input data.

The request is forwarded to the UserService.

The UserService creates a new User instance.

The UserRepository stores the user in the database.

The database confirms the insertion.

The API returns a success response to the client.

Place Creation Flow

The Place Creation Sequence Diagram illustrates how a user creates a new place listing.

Flow description:

The client sends a request to create a new place.

The API receives and validates the request.

The request is forwarded to the Place business logic component.

A new Place instance is created.

The repository stores the place in the database.

The database confirms the insertion.

The API returns the result to the client.

Review Submission Flow

The Review Submission Sequence Diagram shows how users submit reviews for places.

Flow description:

The user submits a review request through the API.

The API validates the request data.

The request is forwarded to the Review service.

A new Review instance is created.

The repository stores the review in the database.

The database confirms the operation.

The API returns a success or error response.

5. Design Notes
Layered Architecture

The system is divided into multiple layers to separate responsibilities and improve maintainability.

Object-Oriented Design

The project applies object-oriented principles such as encapsulation and abstraction to structure the system into reusable entities.

Facade Pattern

The Presentation Layer acts as a simplified interface for interacting with the system’s internal models.

Repository Pattern

Repositories isolate database operations from the business logic, making the system easier to maintain and extend.

